#Text=George Eld
#Text=For the antiquary , see George Eld ( antiquary ) .
#Text=George
#Text=Eld

#Text=( died 1624 ) was a London printer of the Jacobean era , who produced important works of English Renaissance drama and literature , including key texts by William Shakespeare , Ben Jonson , Christopher Marlowe , and Thomas Middleton .
#Text=Eld was the son of a carpenter from Derbyshire .
#Text=He served an eight-year apprenticeship to bookseller Robert Bolton , starting in 1592 , and became a " freeman " ( a full member ) of the Stationers Company on 13 January 1600 .
#Text=He established himself in his own printing business in 1604 , at the sign of the White Horse in Fleet Lane , by marrying the widow of not one but two master printers . [ 1 ]
#Text=His shop featured two or perhaps three presses , and four compositors – a substantial operation for the time .
#Text=Eld entered into a partnership with Miles Fletcher in 1617 ; Fletcher took over the business after Eld died of plague in 1624 . [ 2 ]
#Text=Printer

#Text=In Eld 's historical era , most stationers concentrated on either printing or bookselling ; and most publishing was done by the booksellers , who commissioned the printers to print their works .
#Text=Eld was primarily a printer during his career , working on specific projects for specific booksellers .

#Text=In his two-decade career , Eld printed a wide variety of works ; when the printer is identified on title pages only with initials , researchers have used Eld 's characteristic title-page device , " two volutes with foliage , " for supporting evidence .

#Text=He is the " G. E. " who printed William Camden ' s Remains of a Greater Work ( 1605 ) for Simon Waterson , John Selden ' s The Duello ( 1610 ) for John Helme , and Peter Gosselin 's The State Mysteries of the Jesuits ( 1623 ) for Nicholas Bourne .
#Text=Thorpe
#Text=Eld worked regularly for Thomas Thorpe ; the two produced more than twenty titles together .
#Text=These included the first quartos of Jonson 's Sejanus ( 1605 ) , Volpone ( 1606 ) , and The Masque of Blackness and The Masque of Beauty ( in one volume , 1608 ) .
#Text=They also issued John Marston ' s What You Will ( 1607 ) , and George Chapman ' s All Fools ( 1605 ) and The Conspiracy and Tragedy of Charles , Duke of Byron ( 1608 ) . [ 3 ]

#Text=Thorpe and Eld were also involved in two " dubious publishing enterprises " – one , a failed attempt to print a work to which they did not have the rights , and the other , a successful such attempt of some work by Thomas Coryat . [ 4 ]

column1: #Text=Shakespeare
#Text=Thorpe and Eld 's most significant project was the 1609 first edition of Shakespeare 's Sonnets .

#Text=In 1612 , Thorpe and Eld also issued a work of modern Shakespearean controversy , the Funeral Elegy that Donald Foster proposed as a work by Shakespeare , [ 5 ] without convincing most scholars and critics . [ 6 ]
#Text=More Shakespeare : Eld printed the 1609 quarto of Troilus and Cressida , for Richard Bonian and Henry Walley .

#Text=Some critics have complained that the text in this volume is so poor that it should be classed as a " bad quarto ; " how much blame for this should fall on Eld , and how much is due to a faulty manuscript source that Eld had to work with , is open to question . ( Eld 's Sejanus text , in contrast , is excellently printed . ) Eld has also been identified as the printer of John Smethwick ' s third quarto of Hamlet ( 1611 in literature ) . [ 7 ]
#Text=Others
#Text=Eld also printed the 1609 second quarto of Marlowe 's Doctor Faustus for John Wright .
#Text=And for William Aspley , he printed one of the most controversial plays of the period , Eastward Ho ( three editions , 1605 ) .
#Text=Eld printed first editions of a range of other texts in Jacobean drama : [ 8 ]
#Text=Samuel Daniel
#Text=' s The Queen 's Arcadia ( 1606 ) , for publisher Simon Waterson .
#Text=The anonymous Return from Parnassus ( 1606 ) , for John Wright .
#Text=The anonymous Caesar 's Revenge ( 1606 ) , also for John Wright .
#Text=Barnabe Barnes
#Text=' s The Devil 's Charter ( 1607 ) , again for John Wright .
#Text=Day
#Text=, Rowley , and Wilkins 's The Travels of the Three English Brothers ( 1607 ) , once again for Wright .
#Text=Thomas Tomkis
#Text=' s Lingua ( 1607 ) , for Simon Waterson .
#Text=Lording Barry
#Text=' s Ram Alley ( 1611 ) , for Robert Wilson .
#Text=Chapman 's The Memorable Masque of the Middle Temple and Lincoln 's Inn ( 1613 ) , for George Norton .
#Text=Nathan Field
#Text=' s Amends for Ladies ( 1618 ) , for Matthew Walbancke .
#Text=Publisher
#Text=Like some printers of his generation – Richard Field is a good example – Eld also published work on his own authority .
#Text=He was active in drama here too :
#Text=Eld printed and published both Q1 and Q2 of The Revenger 's Tragedy ( 1607 and 1608 ) .
#Text=The play is now generally attributed to Middleton .
#Text=Also , Middleton 's A Trick to Catch the Old One , again the first two quartos ( both 1608 ) .
#Text=A printer who published usually had to arrange for a bookseller to sell the work in question ; the title page of Q2 of A Trick specifies that the book is to be " sold by Henry Rocket .

#Text= Yet when the third edition of A Trick appeared in 1616 , Eld was no longer the publisher ; he merely printed the volume for bookseller Thomas Langley .

column1: #Text=Eld published Northward Ho , by Thomas Dekker and John Webster , in 1607 . [ 9 ]

#Text=Eld published beyond the confines of Jacobean drama as well , with works like John Healey ' s 1610 translation of The City of God by St. Augustine . ( That volume bore a dedication to William Herbert , 3rd Earl of Pembroke , signed by Thorpe . ) In 1622 he issued a volume of satires by John Taylor the Water Poet called The Water Cormorant His Complaint .
#Text=He published the types of religious books that were so common in his era , like Bishop Gervase Babington ' s Works , Containing Comfortable Notes on the Five Books of Moses ( 1615 ) .
#Text=And inevitably , Eld published and printed many now-obscure works by forgotten authors .

#Text=The title page of his 1606 edition of Robert Pricket 's Time 's Anatomy bears the inscription " to be sold by John Hodgets " – another demonstration of the printer/publisher 's need for a retail outlet for his products .
#Text=Grimeston

#Text=In 1607 , Eld printed and published Edward Grimeston ' s A General Inventory of the History of France , the book that provided Chapman source material for his tragedies on then-recent French history ( including the Byron plays cited above ) .

#Text=Eld followed this with several other large histories by Grimeston , partnering with fellow stationers Adam Islip , M. Flesher , and William Stansby : A General History of the Netherlands ( A. Islip and G. Eld , 1609 ) , The General History of Spain ( A. Islip and G. Eld , 1612 ) , The General History of the Magnificent State of Venice ( G. Eld and W. Stansby , 1612 ) , and A General History of France ( G. Eld and M. Flesher , 1624 ) .
